<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06029216 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06029216 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; MILITARY; PROFESSIONAL; IRAQ; REPORT; DEATH; AVIATION; ASSAULT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Iraq claimed today that prisoners of war had been hit in air raids by theallied coalition and that at least one was killed.;    Iraq had said last weekthat it was moving some of its 20 or more allied POWs to strategic sites as&quot;human shields&quot; against air attacks, a move condemned in the West as aviolation of Geneva rules on treatment of POWs.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  RAIDS HIT POWS, IRAQIS CLAIM  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Crisis in the GulfSee related articles on page 1A, 13A-16A, 1C, 1B, and 1E  </MEMO><TEXT>     The Iraqi News Agency did not give the nationality of the prisoner it saidhad died. There are seven American POWs.;    The report, which was monitoredin Nicosia, said the allied POW was killed during an attack on Baghdad in whatIraqi military leaders described as one of 65 air raids on Iraq on Mondayevening and this morning.;    &quot;One of the raids hit one of the departments ofthe Ministry of Industry, killing one of the captured foreign pilots, who hadbeen evacuated to that department,&quot; said a military statement carried by thenews agency.;    The Iraqi News Agency said it learned that &quot;numbers&quot; of warprisoners had been hit in &quot;enemy air raids&quot; Monday and today.;    Twenty-fourallied warplanes have been lost in the intensive, daily air strikes thecoalition began launching Jan. 17 on Iraq and Kuwait.;    Twenty coalitionfliers are listed as missing in action, including seven Americans, 10 British,two Italians and one Kuwaiti. In addition, seven other Americans are listed asPOWs.;    Iraq infuriated the allies by parading POWs on national televisionand apparently forcing them to read anti-U.S. statements.;    Reports reachingNicosia said a petrochemical complex near the southern Iraqi port of Basra wasbombarded heavily, and there was heavy damage also in the northern city ofKirkuk, another oil producing region.;    Iran's official news agency said thefire at the petrochemical complex near Basra was still burning today andblanketing the region with smoke.;    The Islamic Republic News Agency quotedresidents of the nearby Iranian city of Khorramshahr as reporting that thecomplex, bombed Monday night, was still aflame and pouring out smoke.;   Basra is headquarters to Iraq's forces in occupied Kuwait.;    In the PersianGulf, a gigantic oil spill Saudi officials now put at about 460 milliongallons -- almost three times the size of the world's largest previous spill.;   The flood of crude oil, which U.S. officials said was deliberatelyunleashed by Iraqi occupiers in Kuwait, was stemmed by a weekend American airstrike on a pipeline complex. International efforts to clean up the spill areunder way.;    In a CNN interview, Iraqi President Saddam Hussein refused tocomment specifically on whether Iraq had dumped millions of barrels of Kuwaitioil into the gulf. But he was quoted as saying: &quot;If Iraq uses oil inself-defense, including in the sea, they would be justified in taking suchaction.&quot;;    The slick is moving toward the Saudi city of Jubail, site of theworld's largest water desalination plant and one of many such facilities inthe path of the spill. Environmentalists call the spill an ecologicalcatastrophe.;    Lawmakers from 24 European countries, meeting in Strasbourg,France, today called the oil spill an offense against humanity and urged thatIraqi leaders be tried for war crimes. The lawmakers make up the parliamentarybranch of the Council of Europe.;    The Pentagon acknowledged for the firsttime on Monday that the seven Americans who had been listed as missing inaction are now considered prisoners of war. All seven had appeared in Iraqitelevision broadcasts shortly after their aircraft were shot down over Iraqiterritory.;    Iraq has repeatedly accused the allies of targeting civiliansin their bombardment. The Baghdad government, in a letter to U.N. SecretaryGeneral Javier Perez de Cuellar, said more than 320 civilians have been killedin air raids.;    President Bush, in a speech Monday, acknowledged that someinnocent people were being hurt and killed and said such casualties are &quot;war'sgreatest tragedy.&quot; But he repeated the allies' contention that everythingpossible is being done to avoid hitting civilian targets.;    Iraq's &quot;Motherof Battles&quot; radio -- created by the Baghdad government to broadcast war news-- today said Bush's &quot;crimes will not pass without . . . punishment.&quot;;    Bushturned the accusation of targeting civilians back at Saddam, saying the Iraqileader had ordered &quot;wanton, barbaric bombing of civilian areas&quot; in Israel andSaudi Arabia. Both Israel and Saudi Arabia came under Iraqi missile attackMonday.;    In Saudi Arabia, a U.S.-made Patriot missile knocked out anincoming Iraqi Scud late Monday, raining bits of wreckage onto a farm on theoutskirts of the capital, Riyadh.;    In an attack on Israel -- the seventh sofar -- parts of a Scud-type rocket landed on Arab villages in the occupiedWest Bank, military officials and the state radio reported. It was the firstreported hit in the West Bank, where Arabs have shown strong support forSaddam.;    There were no immediate reports of injuries and apparently noPatriot was fired to intercept the Scud, which carried a conventional warhead.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Nicosia, Cyprus  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910129  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  846  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday January 29, 199100029216,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </